Imagine you have a box of crayons.

One crayon can draw one thing. A red crayon draws red. That's like one agent — it does one job, like reading a file.

A handful of crayons is a pool. You grab 3 red crayons so if one breaks, you still have red. That's what ProbOS does — it keeps a few copies of each agent so one can rest while another works.

Now here's the magic part.

You and your friends are all drawing pictures at the same table. You each have your own box of crayons. If you need a color you don't have, you ask your friend: "Hey, do you have purple?" Your friend checks their box and passes it over. That's federation — each kid is a ProbOS node with its own agents, and they share by asking.

But before you use your friend's crayon, you sniff it to make sure it's not a marker pretending to be a crayon. That's consensus — the other crayons at your table vote on whether the new one is okay.

Here's why it's fractal — the same shape repeats at every size:

Tiny: One agent has a confidence score. It gets better at its job the more it practices. Like how you get better at coloring inside the lines.

Small: A pool of agents picks which one should do the job. The best one goes first. Like picking which of your 3 red crayons has the sharpest tip.

Medium: The whole box (one ProbOS node) figures out which pool can handle your request. "I need to draw a house" → you need brown for walls, blue for sky, green for grass. It breaks the job into parts. That's the decomposer.

Big: Multiple boxes at the table (federated nodes) share work. Your box doesn't have gold? Ask your friend's box.

Huge: Tables in different rooms (future: cross-network federation). Same rules, just farther apart.

At every single level, the same three rules apply:

"Is this safe?" — Before using a crayon, check it won't ruin the picture. (Safety budget)
"Can I undo this?" — Draw in pencil before using marker. (Reversibility)
"Only grab what you need" — Don't dump the whole box out for one line. (Minimal authority)
And at every single level, the same pattern repeats:

Try → see what happens
Learn → remember if it worked
Ask friends → if it's a big deal, vote on it
One crayon learning to draw better. One pool picking its best crayon. One box splitting a picture into parts. Many boxes sharing crayons across the table. It's the same pattern of try, learn, ask — just repeated at bigger and bigger sizes.

That's fractal scaling. Same shape, every size. Crayons all the way down.